    "side_effects_description": "The possible side effect of using Scorzonera subintegra are experiencing nausea, vomiting, developing diarrhea, and suffering from diarrhea, due to its potential to cause gastrointestinal irritation. This is likely caused by the presence of saponins, which can be toxic in large amounts. Scorzonera subintegra can also cause gastrointestinal upset when ingested in excess, leading to an imbalance of gut bacteria. The roots of the plant contain sesquiterpene lactones, which can cause irritation and inflammation in the digestive tract. These compounds can lead to symptoms such as vomiting, diarrhea, and stomach cramps when the plant is used improperly.",
