    "taxonomy": "Scorzonera subintegra is a species of the genus Scorzonera, which is classified as part of the family Asteraceae. This classification is based on its botanical characteristics and relationships to other plants within the same family. The family Asteraceae is commonly known as the daisy or sunflower family, comprising over 23,000 species of flowering plants. Scorzonera subintegra is also often classified under the order Asterales and the clade Angiosperms. Further classification can be found at the rank of kingdom, which in the case of Scorzonera subintegra is Plantae.",
    "benefits": "Scorzonera subintegra is known for its potential health benefits, including antioxidant and anti-inflammatory properties. The plant is believed to have a positive effect on the digestive system and may help alleviate symptoms of irritable bowel syndrome. Scorzonera subintegra also contains prebiotic fibers, which can support the growth of beneficial gut bacteria. Additionally, it has been traditionally used to treat various health issues, such as colds, fever, and respiratory problems. Further research is necessary to confirm the extent of its health benefits.",
